    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-11-06T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-11-06T04:00:00-05:00" n="349"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d349">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/7347: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-11-06T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 6, 1935—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 6—1:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>121. Embassy’s 116, November 4, 3 p.m. Takahashi yesterday admitted to a local
                    press representative that Japanese gendarmes have arrested various Chinese in
                    Peiping because of alleged connection of the latter with the Blue Shirt Society.
                    Takahashi also stated that these arrests were made not with the permission but
                    “with the understanding of the Chinese authorities”. The arrested persons are
                    said to be under detention at the Japanese <hi rend="italic">gendarmerie</hi>
                    headquarters for examination. The Chinese authorities it is stated have also
                    made some arrests. Among those arrested is a brother of ex-mayor Yuan, according
                    to today’s press.</p>
                <p>Takahashi further said that Yuan had not resigned in compliance with a Japanese
                    demand but because of the Japanese attack on him with regard to Blue Shirts and
                    Tangpu members under him and that there had been no demand for the abolition of
                    the Branch Military Council but that he considered the Council a superfluous
                    organ.</p>
                <p>Repeated Nanking, by mail to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
